### 1. Test Public Endpoint (should succeed)
# This endpoint has the "public" policy. Any request, with or without a token, should be allowed.
GET http://localhost:8000/v1/greeter/public/World

###

### 2.1 Test Authenticated Endpoint without Token (should fail with 401 Unauthorized)
# This endpoint requires authentication ("authn-only" policy).
# Since no token is provided, the middleware should reject the request.
GET http://localhost:8000/v1/greeter/authenticated/World

###

### 2.2 Test Authenticated Endpoint with User Token (should succeed)
# Providing a valid user token should pass the authentication check.
GET http://localhost:8000/v1/greeter/authenticated/World
X-Token: Bearer valid-user-token

###

### 3.1 Test Authorized Endpoint without Token (should fail with 401 Unauthorized)
# This endpoint requires both authentication and authorization ("authn-authz" policy).
# The request should be rejected at the authentication step.
GET http://localhost:8000/v1/greeter/authorized/World

###

### 3.2 Test Authorized Endpoint with User Token (should fail with 403 Forbidden)
# The user token is valid for authentication, but the user does not have the 'admin' role.
# The request should be rejected at the authorization step.
GET http://localhost:8000/v1/greeter/authorized/World
X-Token: Bearer valid-user-token

###

### 3.3 Test Authorized Endpoint with Admin Token (should succeed)
# The admin token is valid for authentication, and the principal has the 'admin' role.
# The request should pass both authentication and authorization.
GET http://localhost:8000/v1/greeter/authorized/World
X-Token: Bearer admin-token

###